HEADWORD: Abram-man
<hw>A"bram-man`</hw></mhw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Possibly
in allusion to the parable of the beggar Lazarus in Luke xvi. <au>Murray
(New Eng. Dict. ).</au>]</ety> <def>One of a set of vagabonds who
formerly roamed through England, feigning lunacy for the sake of
obtaining alms.</def> <rj><au>Nares.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sham Abraham</b></col>, <cd>to feign sickness.</cd>
<au>Goldsmith.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Abraid</ent>⟦br⟧
